me from any of various places called Stapleton (in Devon, Gloucestershire, Somerset, Herefordshire, Shropshire, Leicestershire, North Yorkshire, Yorkshire, Cumberland), all named in Old English with <i>stapol</i> ‘post, pillar’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The name is common in Ireland, where it has been established since medieval times in the counties of Tipperary and Kilkenny."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname from the Old French vocabulary word <i>amabel</i>, <i>amable</i> ‘lovely’ (akin to modern English <i>amiable</i> ‘friendly, good-humoured’). The initial vowel began to be lost as early as the 12th century (the same woman is referred to as both <i>Mabilia</i> and <i>Amabilia</i> in a document of  1185 ), but a short vowel in the resulting first syllable was standard, giving a rhyme with <i>babble</i>, until the 19th century, when people began to pronounce the name to rhyme with <i>table</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mabel STAPLETON was born in 1417, in Langwathby, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom. She married Hugh Lowther in 1434. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1450, in Askham, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 33, and was buried in Appleby, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1417–1450":"1417–1450","1418–1475":"1418–1475","1429–1475":"1429–1475","1442–Female":"1442–Surnud","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1434":"1434","ABT 1442":"umbes 1442","1442":"1442","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1429":"1429","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","1440s":"1440 kuni 1449","Lowther Castle, Askham, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom":"Askham, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Edenhall Manor, Langwathby, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Langwathby, Cumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lowther Hall, Lowther, Westmoreland, England":"Lowther